              {
                "type": "output_text",
                "text": "I tried to run a web search to pull up fresh sources, but the search tool failed. I can try again if you want sources or the latest numbers — would you like me to retry?\n\nBased on available historical information, here’s what’s special about this place (Centralia, Pennsylvania):\n\n- A long‑running underground coal‑mine fire: An underground coal seam has been burning beneath the town since the early 1960s. The fire has persisted for decades and slowly spread under and around the town.\n- A near‑ghost town / environmental disaster site: Because of heat, toxic gases and ground instability, most residents accepted government buyouts and left; the town went from a full, active mining community to only a handful of residents and many vacant lots and empty streets.\n- Visible signs of the fire: Visitors have reported steam or smoke emerging from cracks and vents in the ground, abandoned roadways with unusual sinkholes, and patches of scorched earth — all physical evidence of the underground fire.\n- Cultural and media attention: Centralia has attracted national and international attention as a striking example of a long‑term mine fire and its human/ecological consequences. It has been the subject of documentaries, magazine and newspaper features, and is frequently mentioned as an inspiration or comparison for fictional settings (for example, the eerie, fog‑filled town atmosphere in some horror media).\n- Unusual legal/administrative outcomes: Over time the town’s population, postal services and municipal status were drastically reduced (including closure or retirement of the ZIP code and large‑scale eminent‑domain buyouts), making it an unusual case in modern U.S. local‑government history.\n- The cemetery and a few remaining structures: Although most residents left, some physical traces remain — a cemetery still used by relatives of former residents and a few buildings or foundations that mark where homes and businesses once stood.\n\nIf you want, I’ll:\n- Retry the web search and return up‑to‑date articles, government pages, and images with citations.\n- Pull exact dates (when the fire started, when buyouts happened, when the ZIP code was retired) and the latest population estimates.\n- Find maps or directions and note safety/trespass guidance for visitors.\n\nWhich would you like me to do next?",
